The paper deals with information theory and compression of signals, which are typically covered in the cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.ITP (Information Theory and Probability) sub-categories. The paper also discusses the construction of matrices, which falls under the cs.SI (Systems and Control) sub-category. The use of the Slepian-Wolf coding problem suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the cs.MM (Multimedia) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the polarization phenomenon, which is a topic in machine learning and statistics, and may be relevant to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category.
